Thank you all for following this live tweet. Here is the thread re ADB interpellations in the Senate today. #PassADB https://t.co/ngyCdydowV
The consideration of the ADB is now suspended. #PassADB
Sen Villanueva commends Sen Hontiveros for clarifying that the bill does not create a special right. #PassADB
Sen Sotto recommends suspension of the interpellation, to be continued next week. #PassADB
Sen Risa asks where do we draw the line. If we allow a bakeshop to deny services, do we then allow hospitals etc to discriminate? #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that the principle of non discrimination is what is common and relevant. #PassADB
Sen Pimentel asks why the case is being used when the bill is not pattered after Colorado law. Suggests using a different example. #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that the owner would not be coerced to produce the cake, what the bill penalizes is the denial of services #PassADB
Sen Villanueva goes back to bakeshop owner example. Can we require the person to do something against his religious belief? #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that intent is needed. If there is no intent, no crime committed. #PassADB
Sen Pimentel: How will a person know he is dealing with a queer? If queerness is an attitude, it is all in the mind. #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that there are anti discrimination ordinances in the ph, yet in these places no complaint of abuses recorded. #PassADB
Sen Sotto: we should also put in the law what are external manefestation of being queer. People might exploit the provisions #PassADB
Sen Risa says that in the dictionary, straight means two points connected by a line. Yet we use this term to identify. #PassADB
Sen Sotto says that this bill is creating a new dictionary. Why should we make a new definition of queer? #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that the dictionary definition of queer is not what queer in the bill means. It's how people identify themselves #PassADB
Sen Villanueva says that if someone calls him queer, he would be offended. #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that it is up to the person to define themselves as queer, we cannot out anyone. #PassADB
Sen Sotto: for a layman, para mas madali, can you give an example of a queer? Is Sen Honasan queer? *laughs* #PassADB
Sen Pimentel asks what queer means? Intersex? The law should define these terms. Sen Risa accepts and agrees. #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that the bill can be used to protect everyone who would be discriminated against on the basis of whatever SOGIE. #PassADB
Sen Pimentel why claim that this bill is for everyone when it is focused on protecting the LGBT. #PassADB
Sen Risa explains that SOGIE is an aspect of every individual/identity. #PassADB
Sen Pimentel asks if this is an ADB for everyone, why focus on SOGIE? #PassADB
Sen Risa asserts that different discriminatory bases requires different protective frameworks. #PassADB
There has to be a SOGIE based ADB other than comprehensive ADB bec these have different bases of discrimination. #PassADB
Sen Risa: the SOGIE based ADB is for all, may therefore be invoked by a straight man should he be discriminated for being straight. #PassADB
Sen Pimentel asks if everyone has SOGIE, why not just make anti discrimination law for everyone? Why focus on SOGIE? #PassADB
Sen Hontiveros answers yes. #PassADB
Sen Pimentel clarifies, "So everyone of us have SOGIE?" #PassADB
Sen Risa says that it is exactly how the bill is inclusive. Such will still be considered discrimination, based on whatever SOGIE. #PassADB
Sen Villanueva asks what happens when it's the other way around, LGBT owned bakeshop refusing to make man-woman cake. #PassADB
Sen Risa: If we allow bakeshops to discriminate, we also allow LGBTs to be discriminated in orher aspects of social/economic life. #PassADB
Sen Villanueva asks if the example would be considered an act of discrimination if it happens in the Philippines. #PassADB
In the example, the couple was not asking then cake shop owner to marry them, but rather service without discrimination. #PassADB
Sen Hontiveros says that it is not contemplated by the bill to happen. The bill does not talk about same sex marriage. #PassADB
... the cake vendor would be penalized. How does that respect religious freedom? #PassADB
Sen Villanueva reiterates the concept of religious freedom. If a cake vendor would not accept an order of cake with two men figures...
Sen Hontiveros mentioned examples of discrimination based on SOGIE, cases of denial of services in establishments. #PassADB
He said that he in fact have LGBT friends, like Boy Abunda. We note that he took a long pause while thinking of other LGBT friends. #PassADB
Sen Villanueva mentions that he received bashing, that he caused delays on the bill. #PassADB
Sen Hontiveros asserts that these rights are equal. Freedom of religion would remain to be upheld. #PassADB
Sen Villanueva mentions religious freedom as an example. #PassADB
She couldnt accept that certain rights granted to certain groups would have the intent of discriminating others based on SOGIE #PassADB
Sen Hontiveros explains that she could not accept such amendment because it goes against the principle of the bill. #PassADB
Sen Hontiveros answers that the SOGIE is an expanded classification and includes straight men and women. #PassADB
Sen Villanueva asks if the author is amenable to include a provision saying that other rights would not be prejudiced. #PassADB
Sen Hontiveros: Sex in this bill means the binary classification. SOGIE expands this classification. #PassADB
Sen Villanueva asks what the bill means with the term sex. Will it not be covered by the Anti Sexual Harassment Act. #PassADB

RT @lawvoisier: USC SAYS YES TO THE MAGNA CARTA 

YES - 19
NO - 10
ABSTAIN - 1

#PassTheStudentsMagnaCarta
The USC votes to support the Magna Carta.
Rep Agner abstains.
Stat Rep Pangilinan: Ito na ang representante sa bilang. Walang kaduda-duda. Yes.

Engg Reps Belga and Franza vote yes. 
Engg Rep Oria votes no.
Eduk Rep Yapcengco: ang Magna Carta ay magandang ehemplo ng [nagagawa ng] student movement. Yes.
CSWCD Rep Roc: I vote no.
Econ Rep Balindong: We strongly believe that we are better off with the Magna Carta. Yes.
BA Rep Geronimo: No one student movement can limit what the student movement is or can be. A col rep's mandate is to represent the students.
CHE Rep Sevilla says yes.
CS Rep Magalang: Yes. With or without our stands, patuloy pa rin ang campaign for the Magna Carta.
CHK Rep Robeniol: Hindi ko babaliktarin ang boto [ng CHK]. I say yes to the Magna Carta.
CAL Rep Austria: As a college rep, yes.
CAL Rep Austria votes yes.
Rep Villegas votes no.
Rep Ramirez: Parang walang point ang debate. I vote no.
Councilor Toribio: I firmly believe that with the MC, we are much better off and the student movement will be strengthened. I'm voting yes.
Councilor Te and Tolosa vote no.
Councilor Sicat votes yes.
Councilors Alba, Esguerra and Oliquino vote against supporting the Magna Carta.
Coun del Rosario: It's time to give the MC it's place in the history of the student movement. My constituents say yes. I say yes.
VC Carolino, Coun Belen, Coun Castro urge the USC to support the Magna Carta.
Coun Belen: I believe that the Magna Carta strengthens the student movement.
RT @phkule: Councilor Patrick Sicat: If we completely disregard the court, that's anarchy and we don't want that. #USCGA
Law Rep Padin moves to divide the house on whether the USC will support the MC or not.
Coun Sicat: The reason why we were voted by the majority is to cater to what they need. That's what we're trying to do---what the MC is for.
VC Carolino: There is always a chance that we will win and that is what we should hold on to. This is why we keep fighting.
RT @UP_LSG: VC Carolino: The Magna Carta is already the maximum na kaya nating maabot in the legal sense.
VC Carolino: We're not trusting in the legal system but that does not mean that we won't try for this anyway.
VC Carolino: Di natin sinusuko sa admin ang mga karapatan natin. Kailangan pa irecognize ngBOR kasi yun ang process ng pagkakaroon ng policy
CHK Rep Robeniol: Di ba lagi tayong natatalo in legal terms dahil wala pa ang MC? Ito ang mapapanghawakan natin sa legal na laban.
@upalyansa Coun Alba: dapat may qualifier
Coun del Rosario to Coun Alba: Do you believe that we need to have a document that recognizes our rights as students? Yes or no?
Coun Te: Kung sincere tayo na gusto natin idefend ang democratic rights, di tayo [magpapailalim] sa admin. Ipaglaban natin ang edukasyon.
VC Carolino: Let's not clash things that won't even meet. The Magna Carta is the maximum na pwede nating abutin sa legal aspect.

RT @lawvoisier: Beata: "Magkaiba ang Magna Carta sa resolution nung GASC. We don't need to clash them."
#PassTheStudentsMagnaCarta
VC Carolino: Magkaiba ang MC sa isang statement, agenda, sa Diliman student demands. Pinagkakalaban natin ang mga di dapat magkalaban.

Probably should have dedicated a full-length blog post for that Flash x Supergirl thread… but then again where is the time LOL
And one last thing: there really needs to be more Flash and Supergirl cross-Earth interactions. Their chemistry is just so good!!
All in all, I guess I love musicals and superheroes too much to not appreciate this ep. Odd, but really fun, just like any good musical 👏🏻
Also, the song written by Rachel Bloom is catchy and witty enough to be on CXGF, of course. Loved every bit of it, no matter how odd.
Thoughts on the musical numbers: go Pasek & Paul!! That song really sounded like something that would be on the Dear Evan Hansen soundtrack!
I really love how it was an ode to old-school musicals tho (multiple references to Singin’ In The Rain Wizard of Oz included)
I honestly wouldn’t mind having another round of this, but I hope it’s not a dream sequence next time HAHA
It’s definitely a refreshing take on The Flash after almost a whole season of unnecessary melodramatic plotlines lol
The ep couldn’t really match up the musical prowess that glee had in its glory days (tbh), but it was a good, fun hour of tv regardless!
… but I’m nevertheless happy to have witnessed the merging of both superhero and musical genres in this ep, a rare occurrence on TV/movies.
I probably hyped myself up way too much for two years with a different idea of what this episode could have been…
On one hand, the ep does fit into both shows’ narratives, but it still felt as if everything was mashed up together for the sake of novelty
It was great to have a musical episode and all, with the talent they have in both casts, but in general it felt so odd to me…

Marañon: The Sanggunian should not be about itself, should be all about the students and the sectors that it claims to represent.
Marañon: I will support anti-contractualization. This should be rallied by the students. We should invest in this.
Marañon: An issue that we will fully desist is the lowering of age of criminality. We cannot condone the jailing of children.
Marañon on marginalized sectors: Kailangan natin lumapit at sabihin na nakiisa tayo sa kanila.
Marañon on the national situation: What the Sanggunian will be in my term is a proactive Sanggunian.
Marañon on contractualization: In the pursuit of justice, we should demand to change the system that continues to condone these structures.
Marañon on contractualization: As a student government, we have the voice of the students to say that we are against these laws.
Marañon: Contractualization has to be ended within the university.
Maranõn on ADMU contractual employees: We can empower them. Meron silang boses, pwede silang magsalita laban sa mga isyu na napapaloob sila.
Marañon on labor policies: We need to lobby for the regularization of workers. We have to ask them about the realities they are in.
Marañon on sexual harassment: We can support the student and relay the student to local government units such as women's desks.
Marañon: Kailangan may tanggapan ang mga estudyante kung saan pwede sila lumapit.
Marañon: Student welfare encompasses mental health. We need to lobby for the support of administration in catering to students.
Marañon on mental health: We need coordination with offices that deal with students in universalizing services for mental health.
Marañon on religious concerns: Aside from the level of awareness, there should be spaces where muslim groups can participate in dialogue.
Marañon: The Sanggunian should not be something that imposes on sectors. Kailangan tayong tumugon sa mga pangangailangan ng mga sektor.
Marañon on gender issues: There will be committees to address the concerns of our sectors.
Marañon on scholars' concerns: The Sanggunian has subsidies now. What we want is to provide needs-based subsidies.
Marañon: The accreditation process should not be the benchmark of the organizations' legitimacy. They should be given the support they need.
Marañon: Students have a right to organize as stipulated in the Magna Carta, any effort to repress this right will be fought against.
Marañon: My heart is very close to indigenous peoples and giving them a chance to talk to us about their issues is important.
Marañon: We will see to it that CAIP will continue to be a Task Force under my administration.
Marañon: We need to make testing centers more accessible to indigenous peoples.
Marañon: We have to root our solutions to what we do as students through our courses.
Marañon on environmental sustainability: We can contribute through research—bridge the national context to our realities as students.
Maranon: This campaign will not be about me, it will be about the students, it will be about the sectors.
